UID:uxH8IaaOUccBMwtTKg2py
SUMMARY:Write a Feature Film
DTSTAMP:20260405T040308Z
DTSTART:20260415T013000Z
DESCRIPTION:Class Overview\n\nDo you want to write a screenplay for a featu
	re film\, but don’t know where to start? Perhaps you’re a beginner curious
	 about the mechanics of screenplays\, or a longtime writer feeling a bit s
	tuck\, or a director who would enjoy a new perspective. In this class\, ga
	in the skills to turn your ideas into a solid screenplay for a feature fil
	m.\n\nGain the tools and building blocks to help guide each part of the wr
	iting process for a feature-length screenplay. Learn how to be successful 
	with each step\, from idea generation\, to writing and revising\, and espe
	cially outlining and structuring your film.\n\nEach 90-minute class will i
	nclude one or more short in-class exercises\, from brainstorming to writin
	g and revising scenes. In the sixth and final class\, you will have an opp
	ortunity to read an excerpt of your script or present a detailed synopsis 
	to classmates. You’ll be encouraged to work between classes.\n\nWe’ll look
	 at ways to organize your ideas into an outline that can advance progressi
	vely closer to a feature film\, discussing diverse and alternative approac
	hes in your structure that might help your script connect with audiences w
	ithout using clichés. Explore how three-dimensional characters drive plot 
	and how setting\, staging\, and dialogue can be used to tell your story in
	 an energetic\, immersive way. We’ll discuss the differences between writi
	ng a screenplay you plan to direct yourself versus one you’re writing for 
	someone else. \n\nThere will be handouts and/or reading suggestions offere
	d in class. We’ll look at excerpts from books such as Aristotle’s Poetics 
	and Susan Sontag’s Against Interpretation\, as well as film clips and inte
	rviews with a diverse array of famous filmmakers across time and space.\n\
	nGet support and guidance on how to find inspiration for your own personal
	 artistic expression and the drive to finish your project. Explore the man
	y joys that can be found in this unique\, creative\, and multifaceted art 
	form.\n\nLearning Objectives\n\nBrainstorm and organize ideas for a screen
	play\n\nApproach structure in a flexible way that allows for different typ
	es of films\n\nCreate three-dimensional characters that form the basis of 
	a story\n\nHow form can be progressive and new\, just like content\n\nFind
	 your voice and learn to write comfortably and confidently as yourself\n\n
	Who Might Enjoy This Class?\n\nWriters interested in exploring how they mi
	ght approach a screenplay\n\nAnyone who wants to develop their voice as a 
	screenwriter and filmmaker\n\nPeople who have begun a feature-length scree
	nplay and would like the support to continue\n\nArtists drawn to other par
	ts of the filmmaking process who would like to explore the writing side\n\
	nAnyone interested in how films are structured and what screenplays are ma
	de of\n\nFilmmakers who want to create an unconventional piece without sac
	rificing character and structure\n\nNo experience is needed\; everyone is 
	welcome!\n\nhttps://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/write-a-feature-
	film/18345429/2026-04-14T00\n\nFrom SEAtoday - Arts & Culture
URL:https://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/write-a-feature-film/1834
	5429/2026-04-14T00
LOCATION:Seattle Central College Continuing Education\, 1701 Broadway\, Sea
	ttle\, WA
